Q2. An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions.

A. Probability that none of the items are defective? [1 Mark]

B. Probability that exactly one of the items is defective? [1 Mark]

C. Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective? [1 Mark]

D. Probability that three or more of the items are defective ? [1 Mark]

Q5. Explain 1 real life industry scenario (other than the ones mentioned above) where you can use the concepts learnt in this module of Applied statistics to get a data driven business solution. [3 Marks]

Real life scenario: Let us assume Myntra introduces a ChatBot functionality to its customers to assist them in the Buying process. They want to check if using chat bot increases the average sale conversion rate. Let us assume average conversion rate is 20%.

Null Hypothesis Ho: Enabling Chatbot has no effect on Sale conversion rate (=20%) Alternate Hypothesis: Enabling Chatbot increases the Sale conversion rate.(>20%)

We can use a large enough sample and test the hypothesis using Z test. We can either accept or reject the Hypothesis using the p value. (Confidance interval of 95%)

#Calculating new datapoints to help in analysis
df1['TeamVintage']=2015-df1['TeamLaunch'] # Number of years since launch of team. I am assuming this data is from 2015 as the olderst Team was launched in 1929 and has played maximum 86 Tournaments. So have assumed current Year as 1929+86=2015. I am also assuming that Tournament happens once in a Year.
df1['AvgScore']=df1['Score']/df1['PlayedGames'] # Average Score per game
df1['WinRate']=df1['WonGames']/df1['PlayedGames'] # Average Win Rate
df1['LossRate']=df1['LostGames']/df1['PlayedGames'] # Average Loss Rate
df1['AvgBasketScoredPerGame']=df1['BasketScored']/df1['PlayedGames'] # Average Basket Scored Per Game
df1['AvgBasketGivenPerGame']=df1['BasketGiven']/df1['PlayedGames'] # Average Basket Given Per Game
df1['NetBasketScoredPerGame']=df1['AvgBasketScoredPerGame']-df1['AvgBasketGivenPerGame'] # Net Basket Scored Per Game
df1['TournamentChampionPercentage']=df1['TournamentChampion']/df1['Tournament'] # Championships Win Rate
df1['TournamentRunnerPercentage']=df1['Runner-up']/df1['Tournament'] # Runner-up Rate
df1['WinnerOrRunnerPercentage']=df1['TournamentChampionPercentage']+df1['TournamentRunnerPercentage'] # Championship winner or Runner Up Rate
df1.head()

Time Series Data: It would be great if we had a time series data available for the analysis. It would have helped to see if Team Performance has changed in recent years and we could have also considered the same for taking decision.

Quality: The shared data had special character '-'. In the current context I am assuming it is used for 0 values. However Team 61 has '-' for most of fields field even though they have participated in 1 tournament.

Quantity: We have summarized details for 61 teams in the shared dataset. However to derive any meaningful insigts by applying ML algoritams we will need more data points. It would have helped if had details of more teams if available. Also details of which Team are already under Contract with Competitors would have helped for final recommendations.

Variety: We were shared a csv file with summarized performance details for 61 teams. We could have also used data from other sources like Social Media to understand which teams are most popular .

Velocity: As per the data the olderst Team was launched in 1929 and has played maximum 86 Tournaments. So have assumed current Year as 1929+86=2015. Since we are in 2021 we are missing 6 Years of data.

Veracity: The average baskets scored per game is in range of 0.77 to 2.15 which is too low. Similarly Average Basket given per game is in range of 1.12 to 2.83 which again is too low.

Visibly the distribution of Funds looks similar for both Operating and Closed accounts. We can verify if there is a difference or not using Hypothesis Testing.

Write the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis. [1 Mark]

Null Hypothesis Ho: There is no difference in Mean Fund Values for both companies that are still operating vs companies that closed down.

Alternate Hyporthesis Ha: Mean Fund value for Operating companies is not equal to Mean Fund value of closed companies.

Test for significance and conclusion [1 Mark]

In [400]:
# For this testing we are keeping alpha=0.05 (95% Confidance)

alpha = 0.05 
from statsmodels.stats.weightstats import ztest

sample1 = df3.loc[df3.OperatingState == 'Operating', 'Funds_in_million']
sample2 = df3.loc[df3.OperatingState =='Closed', 'Funds_in_million']



test_statistic, p_value = ztest(sample1, sample2)

if p_value <= alpha:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value, 3)} < {alpha} (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis')
else:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value,3)} > {alpha} (alpha) the difference is not significant and, we fail to reject the Null hypothesis''')

Since the p-value, 0.192 > 0.05 (alpha) the difference is not significant and, we fail to reject the Null hypothesis

In [401]:
# For this testing we are keeping alpha=0.05 (95% Confidance)

alpha=0.05
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

z_statistic, p_value = proportions_ztest([Operating_contestant, Operating_Winners], [Contestants, Winners])

if p_value <= alpha:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value, 3)} < {alpha} (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis')
else:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value,3)} > {alpha} (alpha) the difference is not significant and we fail to reject the Null hypothesis''')
